## Working time is not a fixed number

One of the most common questions is:

“How much time do you have before clamping?”

There is no single answer.

Working time depends on:

- glue temperature  
- room temperature  
- thickness of the veneer  
- size of the surface  

In practice, the working window is short.

This is why the process must be prepared in advance and executed without interruption.

## PVA adhesives and cold creep

PVA glues behave differently.

They remain slightly flexible after curing.

This introduces a known phenomenon:

cold creep.

Over time, under stress, the material can slowly shift.

This may lead to:

- surface undulations  
- loss of flatness  
- movement in laminated elements  

This is not a defect of a specific product.

It is a characteristic of the adhesive system.

## Titebond III – controlled use

Titebond III is a modified PVA adhesive.

It creates a harder glue line than standard PVAs.

Because of this, it is often used for:

- veneering in vacuum bags  
- cold laminations  

In my own practice, I use it with a clear limitation.

I apply it only in elements that are later structurally constrained.

For example:

- panels fixed within a frame  
- elements locked into a larger construction  

In these cases, movement is restricted, and the risk of cold creep is significantly reduced.

## When stiffness matters – urea formaldehyde

For elements that are:

- structural  
- load-bearing  
- exposed to long-term stress  

I use urea formaldehyde resin.

It creates a much stiffer glue line.

This makes it more stable over time, especially in applications where movement cannot be controlled by the structure.

## No universal glue

There is no single “best glue” for veneering or lamination.

Each adhesive defines:

- how the process behaves  
- how much control you have  
- how the material performs over time  

Choosing glue is not a secondary decision.

It is part of the design of the object.

## Veneering as a system

Glue selection cannot be separated from:

- veneer thickness  
- substrate type  
- pressure method  
- structural context  

